\b\i\f1\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af42\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \i0\f31506\fs24\insrsid11800560\charrsid2578727 1. Subject Line Should Be Concise
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11800560 \rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af42 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f31506\insrsid11800560\charrsid2578727 The subject line is the most important component of an email. It\rquote s what the recipient sees before they can start reading your email and is meant to be a descriptor of your actual email content. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af42 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid1068553\charrsid2578727 So,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af42 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid11800560\charrsid2578727  it\rquote s a good idea to keep your email subject short and to the point. Try to summarize what you\rquote 
re conveying in the email in around 5 words.
\par For example, if you\rquote re emailing an update to your team that the scheduled meeting this evening has been postponed by 2 hours, using a subject line such as \'93Meeting Time Changed\'94 instead of \'93Meeting Update\'94 is a far better idea.
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s2\ql \li0\ri0\sl500\slmult0\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11800560 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af1\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
