\b\i\f1\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af42\afs24 \ltrch\fcs0 \i0\f31506\fs24\cf19\insrsid11800560\charrsid2578727 3. Don\rquote t Abuse the CC Option
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3687428 \rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af42 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f31506\insrsid11800560\charrsid2578727 Most email users are unaware of the true usage of the CC and BCC options when composing an email. You\rquote ll often find yourself at the receiving end of an email that has 50+ recipients CC\rquote d in the email, 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af42 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\cf6\insrsid11800560\charrsid2578727 where the sender has no concern about anyone\rquote s privacy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af42 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid11800560\charrsid2578727 .
\par Remember, the CC (Carbon Copy) option is best used when you want to send an email to someone while keeping others in the loop, such as when sending a quotation to a client while keeping your boss in CC. It\rquote 
s important to understand that when using the CC option, everyone involved in the email can see who\rquote s been CC\rquote d, and it\rquote s a good practice to only CC those people who are involved with the contents of the email.
\par On the other hand, the BCC (Blind Carbon Copy) option must be used when you want to email a bunch of users, but don\rquote t want them knowing who else is involved in the email. This is great for when you are emailing the same content recipients who don
\rquote t know each other.
\par As a general rule of thumb, always pick the BCC option unless you\rquote re absolutely sure that CC is better suited for an email. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af42\afs30 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\fs30\cf20\insrsid11800560\charrsid2578727 
