People always make fun of the comic-sans font in emails, and rightly so. It is considered a good practice to keep colorful text and non-standard fonts away when composing an email. We recommend sticking to the default font options and text color largely i
n black, with any of primary colors (Red, Green, Blue) used for highlighting certain words.
\par Of course, that\rquote s not to say that you shouldn\rquote 
t format your emails at all. In fact, formatting is very important. Make generous use of line breaks and paragraphs when sending long emails. Use bold & italic text where necessary, and give headings to sections \emdash  basically all things you\rquote 
d typically do in a document.
\par Remember, emails should be easy for the recipient to read. If they have to take extra efforts to read your email, you\rquote ve already lost their attention.
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s2\ql \li0\ri0\sl500\slmult0\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11800560 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af1\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
